<emphasis id="B94351525A27FF889FF8021BE441092B" bold="true" box="[189,310,1620,1646]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B888D405A27FF889FF802CCE774080B" blockId="10.[189,1399,1667,1870]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<taxonomicName id="4C37F6C35A27FF889FF802CCE40C09D8" authority="Groeninckx &amp; Janssens &amp; Smets &amp; Verstraete, 2017" authorityName="Groeninckx &amp; Janssens &amp; Smets &amp; Verstraete" authorityYear="2017" box="[189,379,1667,1693]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Astiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="confusa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B94351525A27FF889FF802CCE40C09D8" box="[189,379,1667,1693]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Astiella confusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A270EC295A27FF889EC102CBE4A809DB" box="[388,479,1668,1694]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="4C37F6C35A27FF889D2302CCE65209D8" authority="Groeninckx &amp; Janssens &amp; Smets &amp; Verstraete, 2017" authorityName="Groeninckx &amp; Janssens &amp; Smets &amp; Verstraete" authorityYear="2017" box="[614,805,1667,1693]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Astiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tsaratanensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B94351525A27FF889D2302CCE65209D8" box="[614,805,1667,1693]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">A. tsaratanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A270EC295A27FF889C6B02CBE6FE09DB" box="[814,905,1668,1694]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in having few ovules per locule, broadly depressed obovoid capsules crowned with the persistent calyx lobes, and black seeds that are elliptic in outline and have a ventral groove, but differs in its erect habit (vs scrambling or prostrate), the much shorter corolla tube (
<quantity id="4CCF20A55A27FF889EF202A3E73D0842" box="[439,586,1772,1799]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="1.6" valueMax="1.7" valueMin="1.5">1.5â1.7 mm</quantity>
vs 
<quantity id="4CCF20A55A27FF889D3002A2E67D0842" box="[629,778,1772,1799]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.15" metricValueMax="9.5" metricValueMin="4.8" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="7.15" valueMax="9.5" valueMin="4.8">4.8â9.5 mm</quantity>
long), the tricolporate pollen (vs 7- to 8-colporate), and the reticulate seed coat surface with favulariate microsculpturing (vs an alveolate seed surface with rugulose microsculpturing).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32DDECB5A27FF889FF8033AE68C08A4" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B888D405A27FF889FF8033AE43308CA" blockId="10.[189,324,1909,1935]" box="[189,324,1909,1935]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
